---
// The smallest example — the whole authoring contract in one element, shown before the
// deeper manual. Semantic HTML in, a CSS variable out; the live card is a real participant
// the shared field measures, wired by the same data-* contract as every other demo.
---

<section class="concept lede" id="start" aria-labelledby="start-h">
  <div class="wrap concept-grid">
    <div>
      <span class="concept-no">Start here — the whole contract in one element</span>
      <h2 id="start-h">Add a <code>data-*</code> attribute. Style the result.</h2>
      <p>
        A body is any semantic element with a <code>data-body</code> attribute. The
        shared runtime measures it, computes its local <strong>density</strong>, and
        writes that back as <code>--field-density</code>. You read that variable in
        plain CSS — the element is still your HTML, still readable with the field
        turned off.
      </p>
      <div class="loop-line" aria-hidden="true">
        <code>data-body</code><span>→</span>runtime token<span>→</span>local density<span
          >→</span
        ><code>--field-density</code><span>→</span>CSS
      </div>
      <pre class="code-block"><code>&lt;article
  data-body="attract"
  data-strength="0.8"
  data-range="320"
  data-feedback
&gt;
  &lt;h3&gt;Semantic HTML participates in the field.&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;/article&gt;

article &#123;
  opacity: calc(0.55 + var(--field-density, 0) * 0.45);
&#125;</code></pre>
      <p class="note">
        That is the entire surface. The manual below goes deeper — the force catalog,
        conditions, and the system that emerges — but every demo on this page is just
        this contract, repeated.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="stage lede-stage">
      <span class="stage-label">live — a real participant</span>
      <article
        class="lede-live"
        data-hot
        data-feedback
        data-body="attract"
        data-strength="0.9"
        data-range="300"
        data-color="#4da3ff"
        style="--cc:#4da3ff; --cat:#4da3ff;"
      >
        <h3>Semantic HTML participates in the field.</h3>
        <p>
          An ordinary <code>&lt;article&gt;</code>. Its brightness is
          <code>--field-density</code>, written by the runtime as matter gathers on it.
        </p>
      </article>
      <span class="hintline">opacity = 0.55 + var(--field-density) · 0.45</span>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<style is:global>
  /* ── Start-here lede: the smallest data-* → --field-* example ─────────────── */
  .lede .loop-line {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 0.4rem 0.55rem;
    margin: 0.9rem 0;
    font-size: 0.8rem;
    color: var(--muted, #9aa);
  }
  .lede .loop-line code {
    font-size: 0.92em;
    color: var(--text, #e8e8ef);
    background: color-mix(in srgb, #4da3ff 16%, transparent);
    padding: 0.1rem 0.4rem;
    border-radius: 5px;
  }
  .lede .loop-line span {
    opacity: 0.45;
  }
  .lede .code-block {
    margin: 0.2rem 0 0;
    padding: 0.95rem 1.05rem;
    border: 1px solid var(--line, #2a2a35);
    border-radius: 10px;
    background: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.34);
    overflow-x: auto;
    font-family: var(--mono, "Martian Mono", ui-monospace, monospace);
    font-size: 0.74rem;
    line-height: 1.55;
    color: #cdd6e4;
  }
  .lede .code-block code {
    font: inherit;
    white-space: pre;
  }
  .lede-stage {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    gap: 0.85rem;
    min-height: 340px;
    padding: 2.5rem 1.25rem;
  }
  /* the live participant: an ordinary card whose brightness IS --field-density,
     written by the runtime because it carries data-feedback. */
  .lede-live {
    position: relative;
    z-index: 1;
    max-width: 22rem;
    margin: 0;
    padding: 1.1rem 1.25rem;
    border: 1px solid
      color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc, #4da3ff) 45%, var(--line, #2a2a35));
    border-radius: 14px;
    background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc, #4da3ff) 8%, rgba(8, 10, 18, 0.7));
    cursor: default;
    /* the one line the example teaches — opacity tracks the written density */
    opacity: calc(0.55 + var(--field-density, 0) * 0.45);
    box-shadow: 0 0 calc(var(--field-density, 0) * 40px)
      color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc, #4da3ff) 55%, transparent);
    transition:
      opacity 0.25s ease,
      box-shadow 0.25s ease;
  }
  .lede-live h3 {
    margin: 0 0 0.45rem;
    font-size: 1rem;
  }
  .lede-live p {
    margin: 0;
    font-size: 0.82rem;
    color: var(--muted, #aab);
  }
  .lede-live code {
    font-size: 0.9em;
  }
  @media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
    .lede-live {
      transition: none;
    }
  }
</style>
